<font color="#FF0000">HIDDEN MEANING!</font><br>
<tt>Sun Nov  2 10:06:41 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
As a cunning linguist, I feel that it is important that I make a contribution here!  <br>
While field stripping my new P-38 Mark VII, I accidently activated the ANGR 62 mini micro chip decoder and word descrambler.  I learned instantly, that &quot;Beouku&quot; was a primitive form of spelling for the French expression &quot;beau coup.&quot;...used by BOC at the rank of MR and below (and all Marines.)<br>
Not satisfied with that simple revelation, I pressed on to further discover that the phrase is often mispronounced, misunderstood, misused and... disorted!<br>
Quickly, I located the small packette of &quot;Krypto 95 software&quot; (stored next to the cyanide capsule in the molar region of my mouth...don't ask..I can't reveal which side!)<br><br>
Here are my findings:<br><br>
&quot;Beau coup&quot; generally means &quot;alot&quot;.  When mirrored in the reflective surface of my P-38 Mark VII (semifore and Morse Code transmitting capability) the phrase takes on a different meaning ...coup beau or pronounced &quot;Coop Boo&quot; is a secret expression used by VA mental health operatives to share information regarding a deadly phobia.<br>
It is a clever code.  Coop means to be confined, limited or restrained..as in &quot;cooped up&quot; i.e. tunnel rats and Marines in the brig.  &quot;BOO!&quot; is suggestive of being scared by someone or something.  It is a natural progression of logic that led me to discover that &quot;Coop&quot; implies the presence of chickens as in &quot;Chicken coop&quot; therefore by scientific serendipity I discovered that Beau coup (reversed) is a clever coding of Coop Boo...phobic fear of chickens or PTSD (Poultry Trauma Stress Disorder.<br><br>
No language is impervious to distortions and misuse: <br>
Drunken Italian artillerymen, jet pilots, hillbillies, and Marines.. in their attempts to imitate Sylvester Stallone.. often utter the expression &quot;Boo-o-o Cooo-o-o,&quot; in the presence of Army Aviators.. a form of Latin ebonics to convey the contracted meaning, &quot;Boy! Is he cool!!&quot;<br><br>
Now that I have posted something technical..I don't feel so stupid anymore.<br><br>
Mustang Two Four
